text:
A tip from a former activist. Stay low to avoid the excessive damage from shrapnels. Avoid rooms (except when it has a hallway, thick walls or when you fortify it) and do not lean against walls due too shock waves. Children often forget this and the results are beyond horrifying. Wear protective headgears or headphones and cover your face & neck with the correct placement of both hands and arms. Stop your car and hide as low as possible. Do not face towards the bomb except for your feets and stay away from windows. Make sure you are in posession of a first aid kit and flashlight. As a former activist for the opressed Palestinians & MENA I feel sorry for you. The adrenaline rush and terror like fear when bombs drop indiscriminately on civilians by the opressors is something very few of us will ever experience. These images still haunt me. Absolutely avoid being in the open because the last thing you want is a direct hit from the blast and check the Protection guide against Aerial Attacks. Flee as far away as possible from the blast radius. After the bombings there will most likely be an air and ground assault. Soldiers wil murder civilians, medical personel, journalists and activists. Depending on the importance of your country, the reliable sources will update the world about the status of war crimes. Top priority is surving the bombings and air assault. Do not be ashamed to flee your country with your family. I've seen many now and many before who had to do so, while the world watched and supported the slaughtering of those same people. Stay strong üëäüèæ

Edit: Unsuprisingly YouTube censored my reply again. I replied to the Mike G comment with primary sources under a second account: SamuraiBirds in the comment section. (non-primary account due too risk of safety). It hurts that the truth can't be said even after all the research and work that you've done as an individual just because you try to help others. Unsuprisingly civilians have been attacked by invading Russian forces.

author: B__W_45

text:
¬†@B__W_45¬† You cant. Youve probably heard the term 'information warfare'.
That always existed of course (which is why the official narratives on historical events from the last century are also not what they say it is). However, with modern technology (also monitoring how people react to things... they have actually psychologists and so working for them) creating much more means to control public opinion, we are now in full information warfare. So you cannot trust any news outlet blindly.

Its a bit hard to explain how to reach truth, but in general:
- It helps if you are well educated in many fields.
- Be sceptical of any information given by people with an interest (any sort of interest, but especially those who directly benefit financially)
- Be aware of what you react emotional to, (specially shocking events), bc at that time the brain is very open to suggestion. It seeks an explanation and is inclined to take the first one that comes along, that is comfortable (fits in their pre existing moral beliefs). This is the basis of 'psy ops'. So whenever you see something, like now in Ukrain, that makes you emotional (fear, shock, over the moon happy, nervous, etc), take a step back and think about what youve just seen. Then consider if you are capable at this time to weigh information correctly. If you think you can, go on. If you think you cannot, you should not watch any more, bc you will be told a lie and accept it.
- It helps a lot in knowing history. The more you know about history, the more you understand where things are coming from.
- it helps a lot if are pragmatic in analysing data. Can separate obvious truth from fiction. Etc.
- Always look at differing sources. The more, the better.
- Try to get real data (scientific data)
- Know that ALL audio and video can be faked in the present day and age. Go to the movies to see what they can make you see as real and realize what they show you is not possible. What are the give aways in such a piece of video? How do they do it? What are the signs that some video is false? Same for audio. In general they shorter a segment, the more cut off it is., the more shady it is, the less reliable it is. Also as for video watch for inconsistencies in fragments. CGI is computer created and it gets better all the time. You have to learn what is possible and what is not, in order ro recognice fakes.
- Know that at this time, certain parties have been using fake (psy op), propaganda at every step of the way.
- Always 'follow the money'. Who benefits from what?

Many more things and not in the least it also helps to train logical thinking, psychology (what is normal behavior in a given situation), etc etc.
I hope this helps you...

As an example
The US blew up (probably) their own ship the USS Maine, in the port of Havana, to be able to declare war on Spain. Of course this wasnt known at the time. But it could have been known that it was dubious and some probably did. and that is because, who was at the time the weaker state, pretty much unable to wage war against the US in Cuba, would have no benefit from blowing up the ship at all. The US however did.
Many years later it seemed the Spanish already had decided that they could never wage war against the US and tried everything to prevent it. This became clear from internal documents made prior to the event, that were much later released.
The US staged many of such false flags and psy ops. One you probably know is 911. Did any arab state, or 'terrorist' org win anything with that? Nope. Who did win? Well the US criminals on top. (and in Europe). It was the kickstart of a multi billion/trillion world wide enterprise taking away rights of peoples and even leading to Iraq war 2. (where no wmd's were ever found)

text:
I‚Äôm a former Moscow correspondent. Don‚Äôt let Vladimir Putin fool you: Russia‚Äôs war in Ukraine is only about one thing.

If you walk the streets of Moscow, you will eventually smell the faint odor of gasoline.

Any crimp on Russia‚Äôs ability to access the European market is a threat to its economic security.

To get it there, Russia relies mostly on two aging pipeline networks, one of which runs through Belarus and the other through Ukraine. For this, Russia pays Ukraine around $2 billion a year in transit fees.

Russia is a petrostate and relies on oil and natural-gas sales for about 60% of its export revenue and 40% of its total budget expenditures. Any crimp on Russia‚Äôs ability to access the European market is a threat to its economic security.

As Ukrainians looked to rising living standards in places like Poland and Latvia that had joined NATO and the European Union, many wondered why they couldn‚Äôt have the same for themselves.

This is where Putin‚Äôs nationalistic impulses kick in. He views the fall of the Soviet Union as the ‚Äúgreatest geopolitical tragedy‚Äù of the past century and the rush of¬† former Eastern bloc countries into the embrace of the European Union, and even NATO, as a great humiliation.

He has drawn a line in the sand with countries that border Russia,¬†invading Georgia in 2008 when it hinted at joining NATO, and moving to destabilize Ukraine when it moved to establish closer economic ties with Europe.

Domestically, Putin has sold the incursions into Ukraine on purely nationalistic grounds ‚Äî even going so far this weekend as to dismiss Ukraine‚Äôs history as an independent country as a falsehood.
